    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26c.52c-52e_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">63-3    Neihardt Collection</note>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">52c</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        Route 1, Columbia, Mo.
                        Nov. 13, 1958
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt &#8212;</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Seeing you mentioned in the Missourian gives me a nudge and I write you again. I can imagine how it feels to be hidden from your audience by the camera curtain &#8212; it frightens me to consider it!</p>
                
                <p>So, first, you know I admire your courage. The camera is your ally for it truly records your face, your voice and your story. The sketches shown are good in that they contrast the visual picture with the reality of word and thought which seem superior to me.</p>
                
                <p>You are too wise to care overmuch about my yelps of pleasure, so I'll tell you how you come to our house and what you cannot see.</p>
                
                <p>Most of my day is spent on campus as staff member or student. By mid-afternoon it is time to scoot home and tangle with realities of food, laundry and the litter of the house. Your program is a real challenge for five o'clock must show progress so I can merit a pause and suspend the hustle.</p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26c.52c-52e_0002"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">52d</fw>
                
                <p>Some days you are speaking over potato peeling at the sink or meat in the skillet, but you are so much at home in my kitchen I'm sure you aren't offended. Your book is open on the table and I can watch you, listen and read as you go along. My younger son is quite concerned at the sacrilege of notes jotted in your book margin, not understanding the importance of recording your comments or my "read agains".</p>
                
                <p>If you smell hamburgers cooking we are even. I smell your campfires and the wood smoke and see mountains in the background. We have some delightful memories of camping in the South Park County of Colorado and one trip that criss crossed the trail of Lewis and Clark. So, though your country was never under foot, I'm sure I've seen it.</p>
                
                <p>Some days you are more formally received in the living room. My sons (eight and ten) show respect for you and are convinced now that all they can expect from mother at your hour is a glassy stare, a wave of the hand and one "uh." So they hie for The Hinkson <del/> till mother returns from class to produce more bread for the bodies and less <del>lill</del> lilies for the soul!</p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26c.52c-52e_0003"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">52e</fw>
                
                <p>For your producer's information, I like the 5:00 pm hour better than 4:30. Previously I often joined you panting and skittery for fear I'd miss a line.</p>
                
                <p>I hope, in your wisdom, you can translate the <hi rend="underline">gargled</hi> words that come from the <hi rend="underline">rattle in my head</hi> into the <hi rend="underline">simply so.</hi> Thank <hi rend="caps">you</hi> for coming &#8212;</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Mrs. Ted Fisher</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
